    Abstract

    Reports of experimental determinations of solubility for 30 ternary systems of C4–C10 alcohols with hydrocarbons and water are exhaustively compiled and critically evaluated. Reports of experimental determination of solubility that appeared in the primary literature prior to the middle of 2012 are included. For seven systems, sufficient data (two or more independent desterminations) for critical evaluation are available. All data are expressed as mass percent and mole fraction as well as the originally reported units. In addition to the standard evaluation criteria used throughout the Solubility Data Series, two additional criteria were used for each of the evaluated systems. These systems include two binary miscibility gaps in the alcohol + water and hydrocarbon + water subsystems. The binary tie lines were compared with the recommended values published previously and with values obtained with a predictive NRTL model.

For ternary system data to be recommended, binary tie lines that were reported together with the ternary data must agree with these recommended values. When binary tie-line data are not reported but sufficient data are available, ternary tie lines were extrapolated to relevant binary boundaries. Similarly, these extrapolated data must agree with recommended values. In previous publications devoted to binary systems, we judged that data are doubtful if the experimental composition deviates from the recommended data by more than 30% in the case of water + alkane systems and 10% in the case of water + lower alcohols. The same criteria were applied here for the binary tie lines that were reported together with the ternary data. The comparison of the binary experimental and recommended data is given in tables in the corresponding critical evaluations.
    Agreement between reported experimental (or extrapolated) binary tie lines and corresponding recommended values is necessary but not sufficient for acceptance of ternary data. For ternary solubilities, evaluation procedures have not yet been developed. We have tested whether local composition models, such as NRTL or UNIQUAC, can be used for this purpose.
    Experimental data were correlated using the NRTL equation.5858. H. Renon and J. M. Prausnitz, AIChE J. 14, 135 (1968). https://doi.org/10.1002/aic.690140124 For a three-component mixture, the excess Gibbs energy is given by the formula
    GERT=∑i3xi∑j3τjiGjixj∑k3Gkixk,(1)
    where τij = Δgij/T, Gij = exp (−αijτij), and αij = αji. According to the original notation used by Renon and Prausnitz,5858. H. Renon and J. M. Prausnitz, AIChE J. 14, 135 (1968). https://doi.org/10.1002/aic.690140124 xi is the mole fraction for component i, T is the temperature of the system, R is the universal gas constant, gij and gii are the energetic parameters, and Δgij is here defined as Δgij = (gij − gii)/R. αij is the so-called nonrandomness parameter for the pair i+j. For the current purpose we are not interested in gij and gii, but in Δgij values. These values are hereafter called energetic parameters.

The remaining subsystem alcohol + hydrocarbon exhibits complete miscibility for the considered systems. We found that energetic parameters fitted to relevant recommended vapor-liquid equilibrium data are not useful for prediction of ternary solubilities. Therefore, the remaining parameters were adjusted to obtain the best fit of ternary solubility data. To this end, series of tie lines were calculated by a marching method based on the isoactivity criterion starting from the binary hydrocarbon + water subsystem. These calculated tie lines were compared with relevant experimental data. In the case when only saturation (binodal) data are reported, the resulting calculated saturation curves can be compared with the experimental ones. After processing of all selected data, we found that energetic parameters for binary subsystems alcohol with hydrocarbon can be generalized, i.e., Δghw/K = 500, Δgwh/K = −200, and αhw = 0.2 can be adopted for all considered systems. Thus, for calculations of ternary tie lines only recommended data for two constituent binary miscibility gaps are needed and instead of correlation prediction is possible.
    Representation of experimental data with these parameters is far from perfect, but deviations between predicted and calculated values for both tie lines and saturation curves represent correct patterns. Predicted binary miscibility gaps in alcohol + water and hydrocarbon + water subsystems are consistent with calculated “reference values.” Thus, results of prediction with the NRTL equation with parameters obtained with the above procedure were used as a further indicator of data quality.
    1.3. Criteria used for specifying data as recommended, doubtful, or tentative
    This revised work also includes evaluations for all systems where two or more independent measurements of solubility have been reported. In these evaluations, reported solubility values are characterized as Recommended, Tentative, Doubtful, or Rejected, based on consistency between independently determined experimental values and reference values obtained as described in Sec. 1.2. Recommended values are supported by two (or more) independent experimental values, binary tie-line reference values, and ternary predicted values that are all in agreement. Tentative values are supported by two (or more) independent values in agreement with each other, but not with the reference values, or one experimental value in agreement with the reference value. Doubtful values are those for which a single experimental value differs from the ternary reference value. Experimental values that differ from binary reference values, ternary predicted data, and other experimental values are Rejected. If only one source reports data for a given system, the data are not evaluated.

    Auxiliary Information
    Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    The saturation curve was determined by the cloud-point method. Known masses of binary mixtures were placed in a thermostated glass-stoppered bottle and a third component was titrated into the bottle from a microburet with an uncertainty of ±0.01 ml until the solution became turbid. The point at which the mixture became turbid was determined visually. For tie-line measurements, an equilibrium cell was immersed in a thermostat and the mixture was stirred for at least 1 h with a magnetic stirrer, and then was allowed to settle for at least 24 h. The phases were sampled using a syringe and analyzed using a Hewlett-Packard 5890 Series II gas chromatograph equipped with a thermal conductivity detector.

    Auxiliary Information
    Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    The saturation curve was determined by the titration method adopted from [S. W. Briggs and E. W. Comings, Ind. Eng. Chem. 35, 411 (1943)]. The third component was added from a weighed gas-tight syringe to a weighed mixture of the other two components in a 100 ml long-neck flask until one drop (weighing less than 0.01 g) resulted in cloudiness. The flask was immersed in a well-controlled water bath and shaken continuously. Refractive indices of these mixtures were measured to ensure that separation did not take place. The tie lines were determined from mixtures of known composition in the immiscible region. The flasks were shaken well and the phases allowed to separate. Refractive indices of samples of both phases were measured and related to compositions on the coexistence curve. Each tie line was checked to ensure that it passed through the composition of the overall mixture.

    Auxiliary Information
    Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    The saturation curve was determined by the titration method adopted from [S. W. Briggs and E. W. Comings, Ind. Eng. Chem. 35, 411 (1943)]. The third component was added from a weighed gas-tight syringe to a weighed mixture of the other two components in a 100 ml long-neck flask until one drop (weighing less than 0.01 g) resulted in cloudiness. The flask was immersed in a well-controlled water bath and shaken continuously. Refractive indices of these mixtures were measured to ensure that separation did not take place. The tie lines were determined from mixtures of known composition in the immiscible region. The flasks were shaken well and the phases allowed to separate. Refractive indices of samples of both phases were measured and related to compositions on the coexistence curve. Each tie line was checked to ensure that it passed through the composition of the overall mixture.

Chem. Ref. Data 36, 59 (2007). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.2366707 52. A. Mączyński, D. G. Shaw, M. Góral, B. Wiśniewska−Gocłowska, A. Skrzecz, I. Owczarek, K. Błażej, M.-C. Haulait-Pirson, G. T.     Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    The tie lines were determined by the standard additions method.     Auxiliary Information
    Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    The saturation curve was determined by the titration method adopted from [S. W. Briggs and E. W. Comings, Ind. Eng. Chem. 35, 411 (1943)]. The third component was added from a weighed gas-tight syringe to a weighed mixture of the other two components in a 100 ml long-neck flask until one drop (weighing less than 0.01 g) resulted in cloudiness. The flask was immersed in a well-controlled water bath and shaken continuously. Refractive indices of these mixtures were measured to ensure that separation did not take place. The tie lines were determined from mixtures of known composition in the immiscible region. The flasks were shaken well and the phases allowed to separate. Refractive indices of samples of both phases were measured and related to compositions on the coexistence curve. Each tie line was checked to ensure that it passed through the composition of the overall mixture.

    Auxiliary Information
    Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    The saturation curve was determined by the titration method adopted from [S. W. Briggs and E. W. Comings, Ind. Eng. Chem. 35, 411 (1943)]. The third component was added from a weighed gas-tight syringe to a weighed mixture of the other two components in a 100 ml long-neck flask until one drop (weighing less than 0.01 g) resulted in cloudiness. The flask was immersed in a well-controlled water bath and shaken continuously. Refractive indices of these mixtures were measured to ensure that separation did not take place. The tie lines were determined from mixtures of known composition in the immiscible region. The flasks were shaken well and the phases allowed to separate. Refractive indices of samples of both phases were measured and related to compositions on the coexistence curve. Each tie line was checked to ensure that it passed through the composition of the overall mixture.

Owczarek, K. Błażej, M.-C. Haulait-Pirson, G. T. Hefter, F. Kapuku, Z. Mączyńska, A. Szafrański, and C. L. Young, J. Phys. Chem. Ref. Data 34, 1399 (2005). https://doi.org/10.1063/1.1840737 53. A.     Auxiliary Information
    Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    The tie lines were determined by the standard additions method. Water and organic were brought into equilibrium at a given temperature in a thermostat, and samples of each layer were removed with a syringe for analysis. To determine the amount of water in the organic layer sample, a weighed quantity of ethanol was added and the ratio of the water to ethanol peak was measured with a Gow-Mac Series 550 thermal conductivity GC, Chromosorb 101 packing, and a Hewlett-Packard 3390A recorder integrator. The amount of an organic in the water was obtained in a similar way by using a higher boiling material as a standard.

    2.27.2. Calculated values for the system cyclohexanol + cyclohexene + water
    The data of Steyer and Sundmacher4242. F. Steyer and K. Sundmacher, J. Chem. Eng. Data 49, 1675 (2004). https://doi.org/10.1021/je049902w were correlated by the NRTL equation and the procedure described in Sec. 1, where
    Δg12/K=500,Δg21/K=−200,α12=0.2,Δg13/K=−300.886,Δg31/K=1771.907,α13=0.2,Δg23/K=1516.969,Δg32/K=2359.273,α23=0.2.
    Parameters for cyclohexanol + water and cyclohexene + water pairs were fitted to recommended solubility data,54,5554. A. Mączyński, D. G. Shaw, M. Góral, and B. Wiśniewska−Gocłowska, J. Phys.     Auxiliary Information
    Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    The tie lines at atmospheric pressure were determined in a 30 ml glass cell described in [T. Qiu, S. J. Li, S. Y. Li, and Y. X. Wu, Fluid Phase Equilib. 280, 84 (2009)]. The tie lines at high pressure were determined in a 30 ml autoclave equipped with a magnetically driven stirrer, two sampling tubes, and a heating rod. The temperature was controlled by a regulator with a precision better than 0.1 K, and the pressure was controlled by a piston. The mixtures were stirred for 2 h and then settled for 3 h. Samples were then taken from both phases and analyzed. The organic components in both phases were determined using a Varian CP-3900 gas chromatograph equipped with a hydrogen flame ionization detector. The water in the organic phase was determined by a Metrohm 756KF coulometer.

    Auxiliary Information
    Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    First the saturation curve was determined by the cloud-point method. This curve was used to calibrate the gas chromatograph by an internal standard method. The tie lines were determined in an equilibrium still at constant temperature using water from a thermostat (Selected Ultraterm 6000383). Water temperature was measured with a thermometer Heraeus Quat 100 precise to within ±0.01 K. Mixtures were stirred for 1 h and left standing for 4 h. The phases were sampled and analyzed using a Hewlett-Packard 5890 Series II gas chromatograph equipped with a thermal conductivity detector.

    Auxiliary Information
    Method/Apparatus/Procedure:
    The tie lines were determined in 16 ml chromatographic sample vials (HP 5183–4535) as equilibrium cells. These vials were equipped with cap, septa, and Teflon-coated magnetic stirrer bars to provide an intense and continuous stirring for at least 2 days. Next, both liquid phases were allowed to settle for 24 h before sampling with hypodermic syringes. The phases were analyzed using a Hewlett-Packard 6890 gas chromatograph, equipped with an automatic injector (Agilent G2613A) and a thermostatic 100-Vial Sample Tray (Agilent G2614A) directly connected to a ChemStation (HP G2070AA). The internal standard method was applied. Water was quantified using a thermal conductivity detector while a flame ionization detector was used to quantify organic components.
